Reflection (150–200 words)
For Part A, I used HackerRank to complete my first coding challenge. While the "Solve Me First" problem is simple by design, it introduced me to the structure and workflow of an online judge — a system I will use extensively throughout my CSE degree for practice, placement preparation, and potentially competitive programming. HackerRank's clean interface and instant feedback made it an ideal starting point.
For Part B, I used Google Forms to build a Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz for my batchmates. What made this task genuinely interesting was thinking from the perspective of a quiz designer rather than a test-taker: I had to identify the most common misconceptions about digital literacy and frame questions that would expose them. The linked Google Sheet response view was particularly useful — it shows how Google Workspace tools connect with each other to create lightweight but powerful workflows, without needing any coding at all.
Together, these two platforms represent two essential modes of working in a digital career: individual problem-solving (HackerRank) and collaborative, tool-assisted productivity (Google Workspace). Both will be part of my toolkit throughout my four years at VIT and beyond.
